Filter Run Composition Gotchas

These gotchas are about how multiple filter runs interact. Understanding `~`, `+`, `:filter` scope, and space-separated runs is critical for building dynamic lists.

---

1. `~` (else) only fires on truly empty output — not on "0" or falsy values

The `~` prefix means "use this run only if ALL previous runs produced no output at all". It does NOT check for "0", empty strings, or falsy values — only for zero items in the result set.

`+[count[]]` ALWAYS produces output (the string `"0"` or `"5"` etc.), so `~` after it NEVER fires.

```
<!-- BROKEN — count[] returns "0" (a string), so ~ never fires -->
[rrt.type[project]status[active]] +[count[]] ~[[0]]

<!-- BROKEN — same problem, "0" is output, not empty -->
[rrt.type[project]status[planned]] +[count[]] ~[<fallback>]

<!-- CORRECT — test count with match[] instead of ~ -->
<$let total={{{[rrt.type[project]status[active]count[]]}}}>
<%if [<total>match[0]]%>No projects found.<%endif%>
</$let>

<!-- CORRECT — use $list with emptyMessage -->
<$list filter="[rrt.type[project]status[active]]"
  emptyMessage="No projects found.">
  ...
</$list>
```

Rule: Never use `~` after `+[count[]]`. Use `$list emptyMessage` or `$let` + `<%if%>` for empty-state handling.

---

2. `:filter` applies to ALL accumulated items, not just the last run

When you have multiple space-separated runs followed by `:filter`, the filter applies to every item accumulated so far — including items from earlier runs.

```
<!-- BROKEN — :filter also tests "sec:osaca" which has no status field -->
[[sec:osaca]] [rrt.type[project]field:parent[work/mgm/osaca]] :filter[<currentTiddler>get[status]match[active]]
<!-- Result: sec:osaca is filtered OUT because get[status] returns nothing for it -->

<!-- CORRECT — filter before merging -->
<$let filtered-projects={{{[rrt.type[project]field:parent[work/mgm/osaca]status[active]join[ ]]}}}>
  [[sec:osaca]] [enlist<filtered-projects>]
</$let>

<!-- CORRECT — apply :filter only to the run that needs it -->
[rrt.type[project]field:parent[work/mgm/osaca]status[active]]
<!-- then prepend the header separately in wikitext -->
```

Rule: `:filter`, `:map`, `:sort`, `:reduce` are run-level operations that act on the ENTIRE accumulated result set. If you need to filter only some items, do it within a single run's operators or pre-compute with `$let`.

---

3. `+` replaces input — it does NOT append

The `+` prefix takes the accumulated results as input to the new run and replaces the output. It is a pipe, not a union.

```
<!-- BROKEN — + replaces the header with project results -->
[[sec:osaca]] +[rrt.type[project]field:parent[work/mgm/osaca]]
<!-- Result: only projects, header is gone -->

<!-- CORRECT — space-separated runs accumulate (union) -->
[[sec:osaca]] [rrt.type[project]field:parent[work/mgm/osaca]]
<!-- Result: sec:osaca, project1, project2, ... -->
```

Run prefix cheat sheet:
- `[run]` or `[run]` (space-separated) — UNION: adds results to the output
- `+[run]` — PIPE: takes accumulated output as input, replaces output with result
- `-[run]` — SUBTRACT: removes results of this run from accumulated output
- `~[run]` — ELSE: only runs if all previous output is empty
- `:filter[run]` — FILTER: keeps only items where the sub-filter produces output
- `:map[run]` — MAP: transforms each item, replacing it with the sub-filter result

---

4. Interleaving items from different sources requires wikitext, not filters

Building a flat list like `section1 item1 item2 section2 item3` where sections and items come from different queries is extremely difficult in a single filter expression. Filters are good at flat lists from one source — not at interleaving.

```
<!-- ANTI-PATTERN — trying to build section+items in one filter -->
[rrt.type[project]each[parent]get[parent]] :map[
  <currentTiddler>addprefix[sec:] ...somehow append children...
]
<!-- This doesn't work — :map returns one item per input item -->

<!-- CORRECT — use nested $list widgets -->
<$list filter="[rrt.type[project]each[parent]get[parent]sort[]]" variable="parent">
  <div class="section-header">
    <$text text={{{[<parent>split[/]last[]]}}}/>
  </div>
  <$list filter="[rrt.type[project]field:parent<parent>status<status-filter>sort[caption]]" variable="proj">
    <div class="project-item">{{!!caption}}</div>
  </$list>
</$list>

<!-- CORRECT — if you must use vtabs, pre-build the element list with $vars -->
<$vars elements={{{
  [[sec:group1]] [source1[group1]] [[sec:group2]] [source2[group2]] +[join[ ]]
}}}>
  <$transclude $tiddler="$:/plugins/rimir/components/vtabs" elements=<<elements>> .../>
</$vars>
```

Rule: When you need structured/grouped output, use `$list` nesting in wikitext. Reserve single filter expressions for flat, homogeneous lists.

---

5. `:map` returns only the FIRST result per input item — it is NOT a flat-map

`:map` replaces each input title with the first output of the subfilter. If the subfilter produces multiple results, all but the first are silently dropped.

```
<!-- BROKEN — only the first person per team is returned -->
[<jfTitle>get[default-participants]enlist-input[]]
  :filter[get[rrt.type]match[team]]
  :map[all[tiddlers]rrt.type[person]contains:team-member-of<currentTiddler>]
<!-- If TeamA has 3 members, :map returns only the first one -->

<!-- CORRECT — reverse the lookup: scan all candidates and :filter -->
[all[tiddlers]rrt.type[person]!status[archived]]
  :filter[<jfTitle>contains:default-participants{!!team-member-of}]
<!-- Returns ALL persons whose team-member-of appears in the source list -->
```

Rule: When you need all results for each input (flat-map semantics), reverse the lookup direction. Instead of mapping over containers to find their members, scan all candidates and use `:filter` to check membership against the source list.

---

6. Conditional filter operators don't exist — you can't toggle a filter step on/off

A common need: show all items when filter is "all", show only matching items otherwise. You cannot make a single filter operator conditional — there is no `[<condition>then[status[active]]]` that injects an operator.

```
<!-- BROKEN — you can't inject an operator conditionally -->
[rrt.type[project] <$if condition>status<filter-value></$if> sort[title]]

<!-- ANTI-PATTERN — duplicated blocks with <%if%> -->
<%if [<status-filter>match[all]]%>
  <$list filter="[rrt.type[project]field:parent<parent>sort[title]]">...</$list>
<%else%>
  <$list filter="[rrt.type[project]field:parent<parent>status<status-filter>sort[title]]">...</$list>
<%endif%>

<!-- CORRECT — build the filter string dynamically with $let -->
<$let
  base="[rrt.type[project]field:parent<parent>"
  status-part={{{[<status-filter>!match[all]then[status<status-filter>]]}}}
  full-filter={{{[<base>addsuffix<status-part>addsuffix[sort[title]]]}}}>
<$list filter={{{[subfilter<full-filter>]}}} variable="proj">...</$list>
</$let>

<!-- SIMPLEST — use a filter that naturally handles "all" -->
<$list filter="[rrt.type[project]field:parent<parent>] +[<status-filter>match[all]] ~[status<status-filter>]">
<!-- But this gets complex fast — prefer the $let approach above -->
```

Rule: When a filter needs conditional operators, pre-build the filter string with `$let` and `addsuffix`. Don't duplicate `$list` blocks with `<%if%>`/`<%else%>` — it's fragile and verbose.
